Of the '''churches of the Swedish island of [[Gotland]]''', 93 – the vast majority – are medieval. 92 of these are located on the countryside,<ref name=lansstyrelsenkyrkor>{{cite web |url= http://www.lansstyrelsen.se/gotland/Sv/samhallsplanering-och-kulturmiljo/byggnadsvard/kyrkor/Pages/index.aspx|title= Kyrkor|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= |publisher= Gotland County Administrative Board|language=Swedish|accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref> with only [[Visby Cathedral]] remaining within the [[City wall of Visby|city wall]] of [[Visby]], the main town of the island. However, during the [[Middle Ages]], the number of churches was even larger, with at least 12 churches in Visby and an additional large number in the countryside. Some of these are still visible as more or less well-preserved ruins. For further information about these ruined churches, see [[list of church ruins on Gotland]].<ref name="gotkyrkor">{{cite book |editor1-last=Lagerlöf|editor1-first=Erland|authorlink= |title= Gotlands kyrkor|language=Swedish|url= |year= 1973|publisher= Rabén & Sjögren|location= Uddevalla|isbn= 9129410355}}</ref>
{{multiple image | direction = vertical | width = 200 | footer = The development of church architecture on Gotland. Top: [[Anga Church, Gotland|Anga]], an unaltered Romanesque church. Middle: [[Garde Church|Garde]]; rebuilding started but not finished. Bottom: rebuilding complete at [[Rone Church|Rone]], finished c. 1300 | image1 = Igrexa de Anga.jpg | alt1 = Anga Church | caption1 = | image2 = Garda View 01.jpg | alt2 = Garde Church | caption2 = | image3 = ISRonekyrka.JPG | alt3= Rone Church }}
==Background== Gotland began to gradually abandon [[Norse religion]] and adopt [[Christianity]] during the 11th century.<ref name="DMG">{{cite book |last= Andrén|first= Anders|authorlink= |title= Det Medeltida Gotland. En arkeologisk guidebok|trans-title=Medieval Gotland. An archaeological guide book. |url= http://libris.kb.se/bib/12028545|year= 2011|publisher= Historiska Media|location= Lund|language=Swedish|isbn= 978-91-85873-83-8}}</ref> The first churches to be built on Gotland were wooden, built in the manner of [[stave church]]es.<ref name=lansstyrelsenkyrkor/> None of these have survived intact. The most well-preserved remains, today in the [[Swedish History Museum]], are those of [[Hemse stave church]].<ref name="gotkyrkor"/> Traces and archaeological evidence of earlier stave churches have been discovered in ten different sites on Gotland.<ref name="DMG"/> The remains point to an artistic decoration reminiscent of [[Viking art]].<ref name=kulturen>{{cite book |last1= Jonsson|first1= Marita|last2= Lindquist|first2= Sven-Olof|last3= Hejdström|first3= Raymond|date= 1999|title= Vägen till kulturen på Gotland|edition= 6th|url= http://libris.kb.se/bib/7768519|location= Visby|publisher= Gotlands fornsal|page= |isbn= 91-88036-32-4}}</ref>
Stone churches began to replace wooden churches during the 12th century.<ref name=lansstyrelsenkyrkor/> These churches were [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] in style, with influences coming mainly from [[Architecture of Denmark|Denmark]] and western [[Architecture of Germany|German]] architecture,<ref name="gotkyrkor"/> but to a limited extent also from the [[Byzantine architecture|Byzantine Empire]].<ref name=kulturen/> Importantly, the construction of [[Lund Cathedral]] in [[Scania]] established a source of influences in the relative vicinity. Likewise, the 1164 establishment of the [[Cistercians|Cistercian]] monastery of [[Roma Abbey]] on Gotland led to strong [[Cistercian architecture|Cistercian influences]] in the following period of church construction. These Romanesque churches were sometimes decorated internally with [[Church frescos in Sweden|frescos]]. Here also, the influences came most often from the west and south, but sometimes also from [[Russian culture|Russia]]. Similarly, the churches were adorned with stone sculpture, notably decorated [[baptismal font]]s. Here, too, influences came from both the west and the east,<ref name="gotkyrkor"/> but the sculptors themselves seem to have been native Gotlanders.<ref name=kulturen/> Finally, such churches also occasionally display wooden sculptures, such as [[triumphal cross]]es. These display a more markedly uniform western style, with influences coming from France or western Germany.<ref name="gotkyrkor"/> [[File:Martebo kyrka church medieval servant Egypticus.jpg|thumb|left|During the Gothic era, the church portals were often decorated with sculptures, such as these at [[Martebo Church]]]] During the 13th century, reconstruction works were started on several of these earlier churches. New churches were also commissioned. Gotland was enjoying a period of prosperity thanks to increasing trade, and, possibly, due to its role as a staging area for [[Northern Crusades|crusaders departing for the eastern shore of the Baltic Sea]].<ref name="DMG"/> The churches were made larger and more elaborate. The style began to shift in favour of the [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]], although few churches on Gotland display a pronounced Gothic style. The most elaborate parts of these churches are often the portals, notably the main southern portals.<ref name="gotkyrkor"/> The towers of these churches are also taller and more elaborate than earlier towers (which were often designed with a dual, defensive purpose). Another typical feature is the square [[choir (architecture)|choir]] that lacks an [[apse]] and instead has a straight eastern wall with three windows.<ref name=kulturen/> Internally, frescos and wooden sculpture continued to enjoy popularity, as well as occasionally [[stained glass]] windows. Artistic influences came via Visby from mainly western Germany. At the end of this period, Gotland entered a period of economic decline. Following the [[Black Death]], the invasion of Gotland by [[Valdemar IV of Denmark]] and the [[Battle of Visby]] (1361), and a general decrease in trade, many churches were left unfinished. Hence, several churches on Gotland display a peculiar form, where the [[choir (architecture)|choir]] is in Gothic style and disproportionally large in comparison with the rest of the otherwise Romanesque church. In such cases, reconstruction of the church had started with the choir but was brought to a halt before the whole reconstruction scheme could be finished.<ref name="gotkyrkor"/>
From about 1400, no new churches were erected and the general religious building activity decreases sharply. Internally, some churches receive further embellishment in the form of new [[altarpiece]]s or frescos during the 15th and 16th century. Following the [[Reformation in Denmark–Norway and Holstein|Reformation]], a new type of altarpieces and [[pulpit]]s were introduced.<ref name="gotkyrkor"/> These post-Reformation furnishings from the 17th and 18th centuries are also well represented in the churches of Gotland.<ref name=lansstyrelsenkyrkor/>
The church building activity on Gotland thus took place in the period of approximately 250 years, from {{circa}} 1100 to 1350. Until the early 13th century, the pace of church building was comparable to the rest of [[Scandinavia]]. From then on, both the number and size of new churches increased significantly, until building activity came to a complete halt at the end of the Middle Ages.<ref name="DMG"/>
Only a few of the church buildings on Gotland have been significantly altered since the end of the Middle Ages,<ref name=lansstyrelsenkyrkor/> which is unusual in a European context, since medieval churches were often heavily reconstructed or renovated during the 19th century. The medieval parish churches of Gotland comprise the most well-preserved set of such churches in Sweden,<ref name="DMG"/> and indeed in the whole [[Baltic region]].<ref name=lt>{{cite journal|last= Hansson|first= Joakim|last2= |first2= |date= 2005|title= Lost values & unused possibilities in the medieval churches in Gotland|url= http://www.menufakultetas.vdu.lt/var/uploads/editor/mik_1.pdf|journal= Meno istorija ir kritika (MIK)|publisher= |issn= 1822-4547|volume= 1/2005|issue= |pages= 60–72|doi= |accessdate= 12 October 2014|deadurl= yes|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160304044918/http://www.menufakultetas.vdu.lt/var/uploads/editor/mik_1.pdf|archivedate= 4 March 2016|df= }}</ref>
During the 20th century, a small number of new churches have been built, notably in Visby.
The vast majority of the churches on Gotland belongs to the [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] [[Church of Sweden]], and the [[Diocese of Visby]].
