{{one source|date=April 2015}} {{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Millais Royalist.jpg | backcolor=#FBF5DF | painting_alignment=right | image_size=250px | title=The Proscribed Royalist, 1651 | artist=[[John Everett Millais]] | year=1852–53 | medium=[[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | height_metric=102.8 | width_metric=73.6 | height_imperial= | width_imperial= | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city= | museum= Lord Lloyd-Webber Collection }} '''''The [[proscription|Proscribed]] Royalist, 1651''''' (1852–53) is a painting by [[John Everett Millais]] which depicts a young [[Puritan]] woman protecting a fleeing [[Royalist]] after the [[Battle of Worcester]] in 1651, the decisive defeat of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] by [[Oliver Cromwell]]. The Royalist is hiding in a hollow tree, a reference to a famous incident in which Charles himself hid in a tree to escape from his pursuers. Millais was also influenced by [[Vincenzo Bellini]]'s opera ''[[I Puritani]]''.<ref>Jason Rosenfeld, ''John Everett Millais'', Phaidon Press Ltd., 2012, pp. 70–1, 73–4, 88, 102, 111–12, 192.</ref>
Millais painted the picture in [[Hayes, Kent]], from a local oak tree that became known as the Millais Oak.<ref>Millais, J.G., ''Life and Letters of Sir John Everett Millais'', vol. 1, p.166; See also [http://www.arborecology.co.uk/article_ancient_tree.htm Arborecology, containing a photograph of the Millais oak]</ref>
